abel": "safe", "comment": "appropriate link, uniformity in section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Corrigan"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oklahoma", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Oklahoma, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oklahoma\n| map1            = [[File:COVID-19 Cases in Oklahoma by counties.svg|COVID-19 Cases in Oklahoma by counties]]\n| places          = \n| legend1         = {{legend|#b92919|Confirmed cases through April 3}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]]\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = China\n| confirmed_cases = 1,327\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 51<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/|title=COVID-19  |publisher=[[Oklahoma State Department of Health]]}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Oklahoma]] in March 2020. The first death occurred in Oklahoma on March 15.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Oklahoma medical cases chart}}\n\n===February===\nIn mid-February, an epidemiologist serving as chief medical officer of a small hospital in [[Bristow, Oklahoma]] became concerned that data coming out of China indicated a possible pandemic. He organized a citizens' response team that included a phone chain, teams of teenagers and college students ready to deliver groceries to seniors, and a school feeding program for children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/small-town-battled-coronavirus-on-its-own-as-outbreak-spread-in-a-red-state/2020/03/27/55c727f6-6dde-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Small town battled coronavirus on its own, as outbreak spread in a red state|last=Gowen|first=Annie|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|date=2020-03-27|website=[[Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn March 7, 2020, the first case of coronavirus was confirmed in Oklahoma. The patient is in his 50s and came back from Italy on February 23. He began showing symptoms on February 29.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kemp |first1=Adam |title=First case of coronavirus in Oklahoma confirmed |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5656803/first-case-of-coronavirus-in-oklahoma-confirmed |date=March 7, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |publisher=The Oklahoman}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, [[Rudy Gobert]], a center for the [[Utah Jazz]], was ill before the scheduled game between the Jazz and the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in Oklahoma City. He was taken to the hospital and tested positive for COVID-19. The game was suspended and the [[NBA]] suspended the season that day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldman |first1=Dan |title=NBA suspends season after Rudy Gobert reportedly tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/11/nba-suspends-season-after-rudy-gobert-reportedly-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |agency=NBC Sports |publisher=NBC |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Aaro |first1=David |title=Utah Jazz center Rudy Gobert joked about coronavirus before reportedly being diagnosed |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/before-testing-positive-coronavirus-utah-jazz-center-rudy-gobert-joked-about-virus-touched-microphones |publisher=Fox News |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The entire team and their staff were then tested, using up 58 of Oklahoma's allotted 100 tests for the day. Gobert's teammate [[Donovan Mitchell]] also tested positive. The players and staff returned to Utah and the two positive tests were not counted in Oklahoma COVID-19 statistics.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Valenzuela |first1=Sarah |title=Utah Jazz used more than half of Oklahoma's daily coronavirus testing capacity |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/ny-utah-jazz-oklahoma-coronavirus-20200314-iroayd23q5htrcece466ghiate-story.html |website=[[New York Daily News]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, there were 4 cases in Oklahoma, including the first case in [[Oklahoma City]], a woman in her 60s who recently returned from Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/13/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03132020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Governor Stitt drew criticism for Tweeting a selfie in a crowded restaurant, stating that he planned to continue to \"take his family out to dinner\" despite the pandemic. He later deleted the Tweet.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=Oklahoma governor will continue to 'take his family out to dinner' amid pandemic |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/487846-oklahoma-governor-will-continue-to-take-his-family-out-to-dinner-amid |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 16, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"stittcnn\">{{cite news |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Paul |title=Oklahoma governor who faced backlash over 'packed' restaurant tweet now declares state of emergency |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/15/politics/oklahoma-governor-deleted-tweet-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the number of cases grew to 7, an increase of 75% from March 13. The three new cases were in Cleveland, Payne and Tulsa counties. The age range of patients was 20 to 69.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/15/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03152020 |website=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Governor Kevin Stitt held a press conference to announce executive orders{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 16, there were 10 cases, an increase of 43% from the previous day.<ref name=\"article 5658067\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in Oklahoma |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5658067/coronavirus-in-oklahoma |website=The Oklahoman |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Governor Stitt declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\"stittcnn\"/> The Oklahoma State Department of Health (OSDH) authorized certain facilities to restrict visitors in order to protect those inside. The facilities included nursing and residential care facilities, assisted living and adult day care centers, hospitals, and city and county detention facilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Facilities Authorized to Restrict Visitation |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/facilities-authorized-restrict-visitation |tulsa=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, there were 17 cases.<ref name=\"article 5658067\" /> This was an increase of 70% over the previous day.\n\nOn March 18, there were 29 cases, an increase of 71% from the previous day's total.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news9.com/story/41910515/12-more-cases-of-coronavirus-covid19-reported-in-oklahoma|title=12 More Cases Of Coronavirus (COVID-19) Reported In Oklahoma|publisher=[[KWTV-DT]]}}</ref> In addition, the first coronavirus patient died of the disease in Tulsa. He was a man in his 50s who had been admitted the day before. Testing capabilities remain limited in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tulsa Health Officials Confirm First COVID-19 Death in Oklahoma |url=https://www.tulsa-health.org/news/tulsa-health-officials-confirm-first-covid-19-death-oklahoma   |publisher=Tulsa Health Department |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, there were 44 cases, an increase of 51% over the previous day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/19/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03192020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, there were 49 cases, an increase of 11%. The majority of the cases were in two counties: Oklahoma (19 cases) and Cleveland (11) Counties.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/20/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03202020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, there were 53 cases (an increase of 8%) according to the Oklahoma State Department of Health. The U.S. Small Business Administration approved the State of Oklahoma's request for disaster loans for small businesses that are and will be affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/21/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03212020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, there were 67 cases, an increase of 26% from the day before. In addition, a second patient died. So far, there have been no recoveries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/22/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03222020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, there were 81 cases in Oklahoma, an increase of 21% from the previous day. Thirty-six of the 81 cases are in the 18-49 age group, making it the age group with the highest percentage of cases at 44%. People of all age groups are asked to stay home and practice social distancing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/23/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03232020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the number of cases increased to 106, a jump of 26 additional cases from the day before or 31%. A third person died; she was a woman in her 60s and died in Cleveland County. The OSDH encouraged Oklahomans to stay home, reduce person-to-person contact, wash their hands frequently, and avoid touching their faces.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update COVID-19 03/24/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03242020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Governor Kevin Stitt issued new executive orders that all vulnerable people were to stay at home until April 30 and there would be no visitors allowed to nursing homes or long-term care facilities. In addition, gatherings were limited to a maximum of ten people across the state as of midnight on March 24, 2020. Finally, all 19 counties that had one or more positive cases of coronavirus were to close all nonessential businesses by 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 25, 2020 for 21 days. These include businesses with close personal contact, such as gyms, hair salons, nail salons, tattoo parlors, or any business that has social gathering. Restaurants were encouraged to stay open in order to provide pick-up services.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATE: Governor Stitt orders more restrictions and closings |url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/communities/skiatook/news/update-governor-stitt-orders-more-restrictions-and-closings/article_583f1ab2-56e0-5c8d-81ef-64787da7d7b6.html |website=Skiatook Journal |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, there were 164 cases of COVID-19 in Oklahoma, an increase of 50 cases in a single day or 55%. The age group with the largest number is 65+ with 55 cases. New counties with cases include Adair, Bryan, Carter, Creek, Delaware, Osage, Pottawatomie and Stephens. In addition, two more people died: a man in his 70s and another in his 40s. Both were from Oklahoma County. The OSDH introduced a testing site in Pittsburg County with 100 testing kits, and another in Kay County with limited testing supplies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/25/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03252020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The state board of education voted to close all public schools until the end of the school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kswo.com/2020/03/25/oklahoma-schools-closed-state-coronavirus-infections-rise/|title=Oklahoma schools closed as state coronavirus infections rise|last=|first=|date=|website=KSWO|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, there were 248 cases, an increase of 84 in one day and the highest so far, or an increase of 51%. The Oklahoma State Department of Health reported cases in six more counties: Comanche, Craig, Lincoln, Okmulgee, Ottawa and Sequoyah.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03-26-2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03262020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, there were 322 cases, an increase of 74 or 30%. The death toll climbed to 8 as a male in his 70s in Creek County passed away.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/27/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03272020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> As of this date, there were drive-thru testing sites in four counties: Oklahoma, Tulsa, Kay, and Pittsburg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drive-Thru Testing |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/drive-thru-testing |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, there were 377 cases, an increase of 55 or 17% more than the day before. However, there were 7 deaths, bringing the total to 15, an increase of 87%. Six of the victims were over 65 and one was in the 50-64 age group. The virus spread to Le Flore and Nowata counties. The Oklahoma State Department of Health announced that the University of Oklahoma would have the ability to run 2,800 COVID-19 tests a day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/28/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03272020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, the total number of cases rose to 429, an in increase of 14%. There was an additional death: a man aged 50\u201364 in Oklahoma County, bringing the total number of deaths to 16. The virus also spread to Garfield, Rogers, Seminole and Texas counties. If a county has a case of coronavirus, it must comply \"with Governor Kevin Stitt's 'Safer at Home' executive order that calls for non-essential businesses in counties with COVID-19 cases to temporarily suspend services until April 16.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03-29-2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03292020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Governor Stitt updated Executive Order 2020\u201307 in a sixth amendment that required people from six states to self-quarantine upon arrival by air in Oklahoma: California, Connecticut, Louisiana, New Jersey, New York and Washington. They must quarantine themselves for 14 days or the duration of their stay in Oklahoma, whichever is shorter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stitt |first1=J. Kevin |title=Sixth Amended Executive Order 2020-07 |url=https://www.sos.ok.gov/documents/executive/1924.pdf |website=www.sos.ok.gov |publisher=Secretary of State, Oklahoma |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, there were 481 confirmed positive cases in Oklahoma, an increase of 12%. Cases had spread to Beckham, Cotton and Love Counties. The death toll rose to 17 with the death of a man in Cleveland County; he was in the 50-64 age group.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/30/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03302020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> By the end of the day, the state had received over 60% of its personal protective equipment order from the federal government's Strategic National Stockpile.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/31/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03312020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, there were 565 cases of the virus in Oklahoma, an increase of 17%. Six more people died: 4 men older than 65 and a man and a woman in the 50-64 age group, bringing the total number of fatalities to 23. Currently, 31% (565 out of 1,796) of COVID-19 tests are positive. The Oklahoma State Department of Health reported that the state had ordered millions of dollars of PPE from private suppliers and was expecting larger quantities of PPE, including N95 masks, in the next week.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 03/31/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-03312020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn April 1, the number of cases grew to 719, an increase of 27%. Greer County was added to the list of counties with coronavirus cases. Seven people died of COVID-19: 3 in Oklahoma County and 1 each in Greer, Kay, Mays, and Osage, bringing the death toll to 30. No recoveries have been reported. Thirty-seven percent of tests given have resulted in positive results. There are now enough supplies for 13,000 tests, so the commissioner of health Gary Cox and the governor urged health care providers and testing centers to offer tests to any person with symptoms of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Gary |title=April 1, 2020 (letter to county health departments) |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/sites/g/files/gmc786/f/chd_testing_capacity_4.1.20.pdf |website=  |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The governor extended the safer-at-home order until April 30; this applies to Oklahomans 65 and over, as well as to people with low immunity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stitt |first1=J. Kevin |title=Seventh Amended Executive Order 2020-07 |url=https://www.sos.ok.gov/documents/executive/1926.pdf |website=  |publisher=Office of the Governor, State of Oklahoma |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, there were 879 confirmed cases, an increase of 22%. There were four more deaths: a man in the 36-49 age group and 3 men in the 65-plus age group.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 04/02/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-04022020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, the number of cases increased by 12% to 988. Four women over 65 passed away, bringing the total number of deaths to 38 or 3.8% of cases).<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 04/03/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-04032020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> There were drive-thru testing sites in 17 counties.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drive-Thru Testing |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/drive-thru-testing   |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Oklahoma Attorney General Mike Hunter warned Oklahomans to be wary of scams as residents wait for emergency financial assistance, telling them to ignore emails or texts purporting to offer help in expediting payments or charging fees for the assistance. They can stay up to date by visiting the websites for the U.S. Department of the Treasury or the IRS.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Butcher |first1=K. |title=Oklahomans should be on \"high alert\" for scams as wait continues for stimulus checks |url=https://kfor.com/news/local/oklahomans-should-be-on-high-alert-for-scams-as-wait-continues-for-stimulus-checks/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=Oklahoma News 4 |date=3 Apr 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, cases increased by 17% to 1,159 and the number of deaths to 42. Of the 2,521 Oklahomans tested to date, 46% have tested positive. The Oklahoma State Department of Health announced that the Oklahoma Medical Reserve Corps was recruiting both medical and non-medical volunteers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 04/04/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-04042020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, there were 1,251 cases of coronavirus, an increase of 8%, the lowest percentile increase since March 21. Four more people over 65 died, bringing the total number of Oklahoma deaths due to COVID-19 to 46, or 3.7% of positive cases.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 04/05/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-04052020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, cases increased to 1,327 and the number of deaths grew to 51.  [[Jefferson County, Oklahoma|Jefferson County]] had its first confirmed case and the first death from the disease in [[Pottawatomie County, Oklahoma|Pottawatomie]] occurred.<ref>{{cite web |title=Situation Update: COVID-19 04/06/2020 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/articles/situation-update-covid-19-04062020 |publisher=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Oklahoma\nUpdated April 6, 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 |url=https://coronavirus.health.ok.gov/ |website=Oklahoma State Department of Health |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | County\n! sco